Data Visualization

Today we will be using âggplotâ, an R package for data visualization. These tools will help you create publication quality plots and figures directly from your R code. If there is one thing that you get out of this class I hope that it is som confidence with these tools.

What is âggplotâ? The name refers to the âGrammar of Graphicsâ. This refers to a structured language for building data visualizations.

Visualization Practice

Read Census Data

For this section we will read in a table of US Census Demographic data from https://www.kaggle.com/muonneutrino/us-census-demographic-data. Download the file: âacs2017_county_data.csvâ (google sign in required on Kaggle).

To read data into R we use: read.table() read.csv() read.delim()

census = read.csv('acs2017_county_data.csv') #check your PATH to this file
head(census)

LOOK BACK: How do you write a table to a new file?

ggplot2 Graphics

For help and an overview of all of the graphics types that are available in ggplot check out the R ggplot2 cheatsheet

#install.packages('ggplot2')
library(ggplot2)

Recall: Scatterplots using âgeom_point()â

ggplot(data = census) +
  geom_point(mapping = aes(x = Men, y = Women))

Graphs for single parameters:

geom_histogram()

ggplot(data=census) +
  geom_histogram(aes(x=VotingAgeCitizen), binwidth=500)

But the x-axis is based on the maximum value, not the effective range so the distribution of the data is tough to read.

ggplot(data=census) +
  geom_histogram(aes(x=VotingAgeCitizen), binwidth=500)+
  xlim(c(0,50000))
## Warning: Removed 808 rows containing non-finite values (stat_bin).
## Warning: Removed 2 rows containing missing values (geom_bar).

Density:

ggplot(data=census) +
  geom_density(aes(x=VotingAgeCitizen)) +
  xlim(c(0,50000))
## Warning: Removed 808 rows containing non-finite values (stat_density).

geom_area()

ggplot(data=census) +
  geom_area(stat='bin', bins = 30, aes(x=VotingAgeCitizen)) +
  xlim(c(0,50000))
## Warning: Removed 808 rows containing non-finite values (stat_bin).

For Discrete values: geom_bar()

ggplot(data=census) +
  geom_bar(aes(x=State))

But, this is hard to read. A few fixes:

  • Rotate x-axis labels (Use âtheme()â)
  • Sort states by count (Use library(forcats) â Tools for working with categorical variables)
library(forcats)
ggplot(data=census) +
  geom_bar(aes(x=fct_infreq(State))) +
  xlab('') +
  theme(axis.text.x  = element_text(angle=90))

Challenge 1:

Pick a plot method appropriate for the data in the MeanCommute column.

Graphs for two parameters

Continuous parameters

geom_point()

Scatterplots

ggplot(data=census) + 
    geom_point(aes(x=IncomePerCap, y=Poverty))

See also: geom_jitter(), and geom_label()

geom_smooth

Add a line

ggplot(data=census) + 
    geom_point(aes(x=IncomePerCap, y=Poverty), alpha=0.1) +
    geom_smooth(aes(x=IncomePerCap, y=Poverty)) 
## `geom_smooth()` using method = 'gam' and formula 'y ~ s(x, bs = "cs")'

Countour and density plots

ggplot(data=census) + 
    geom_hex(aes(x=IncomePerCap, y=Poverty)) 

ggplot(data=census) + 
    geom_density2d(aes(x=IncomePerCap, y=Poverty))

One Discrete X One Continuous parameter

Boxplots

ggplot(data=census[1:100,]) +  #an imperfect sample!
    geom_boxplot(aes(x=State, y=Poverty))

Violin charts

ggplot(data=census[1:100,]) + 
    geom_violin(aes(x=State, y=Poverty))

Facetting: Multipanel plots

Plus logical subsetting using the â%in%â operator. (compare matches to a list of values)

ggplot(data=census[census$State %in% c('Alabama', 'Oregon', 'New York', 'California'),]) + 
    geom_point(aes(x=Employed, y=Poverty)) +
    facet_grid(~State) + theme(axis.text.x = element_text(angle=90))
